# AI Integration

## Architecture

### Where AI Code Lives

```
src/
├── lib/ai/                   # Provider config, shared AI utilities
│   ├── provider.ts           # Provider abstraction / gateway config
│   └── types.ts              # Shared AI types (messages, tool results)
├── lib/agents/               # Agent definitions (ToolLoopAgent, custom agents)
│   └── <name>-agent.ts       # Exports agent + InferAgentUIMessage type
├── lib/tools/                # Tool definitions for agents
│   └── <name>-tool.ts        # Exports tool + UIToolInvocation type
├── lib/embeddings/           # Embedding pipeline, vector store clients
├── app/<route>/actions.ts    # Server Actions that call AI (auth + validate first)
└── app/api/chat/route.ts     # Chat endpoint (only if external consumers need it)
```

Go AI code lives alongside business logic in the relevant package. Shared LLM clients go in `internal/ai/` or a dedicated package.

### Dependency Direction

```
lib/tools/ --> lib/agents/ --> app/<route>/actions.ts --> UI
lib/ai/  ----^
```

- Tools have no dependencies on agents or routes.
- Agents compose tools. Routes compose agents.
- UI consumes agent types via `import type`.

## Provider Abstraction

- Wrap LLM calls behind an interface or provider layer — never scatter raw `openai.Chat()` or `anthropic.Messages.Create()` across business logic.
- In TypeScript, prefer AI SDK provider strings (`"openai/gpt-5.4"`) or a gateway wrapper.
- In Go, define a provider interface and inject the implementation.

```go
type LLMProvider interface {
    Generate(ctx context.Context, req GenerateRequest) (GenerateResponse, error)
    Stream(ctx context.Context, req GenerateRequest) (iter.Seq2[Chunk, error])
}
```

## Streaming

- Prefer streaming over batch for any user-facing AI response.
- Use `streamText` / `agent.stream()` in TypeScript; stream via `iter.Seq2` or channels in Go.
- Server Actions returning AI streams use `createUIMessageStreamResponse` or `toUIMessageStreamResponse`.
- Never buffer an entire LLM response in memory before sending to the client.

## Error Handling

- Retry with exponential backoff on transient failures (429, 503).
- Budget guards: estimate token count before calling; reject if over budget.
- Graceful degradation: if provider is down, return a fallback response or queue for retry.
- Wrap all LLM errors with context: `fmt.Errorf("generate summary: %w", err)`.

## Cost Discipline

- Use cheaper models for classification, routing, and extraction; expensive models for generation.
- Cache embedding results for identical inputs.
- Cache static/deterministic AI queries (`"use cache"` in Next.js, in-memory or Redis in Go).
- Track token usage per feature/user — store `usage` from responses.
- Set `maxOutputTokens` (or equivalent) on every call — never allow unbounded generation.
- Tag AI calls for cost attribution when using a gateway.

## Security

- Never log prompt content or completions in production (PII, proprietary data risk).
- Sanitize user input before including in prompts — prevent injection.
- Validate structured LLM outputs with Zod (TypeScript) or struct validation (Go) before use.
- API keys in environment variables only — never in code, never committed.
- Rate-limit AI endpoints per user to prevent abuse.

## Testing AI Features

- Mock LLM responses in unit tests — never call real APIs in CI.
- Snapshot test prompts to catch unintended prompt drift.
- Build eval harnesses for quality-critical AI features.
- Benchmark latency and token usage for cost-sensitive paths.
- Test error paths: provider down, rate limited, malformed response, budget exceeded.

## Forbidden Patterns

- Raw API keys in source code (`OPENAI_API_KEY = "sk-..."`)
- Unbounded token generation (no `maxOutputTokens` or equivalent)
- Blocking LLM calls without timeout or context cancellation
- `console.log` / `fmt.Println` of prompt content in production
- Direct provider SDK imports when a gateway or abstraction layer exists
- Storing embeddings without a TTL or invalidation strategy
- Calling AI APIs from client-side code (always go through Server Actions or API routes)
